"# Appendix C — State machine deep dive

Chapter 10 introduced Mealy and Moore. This appendix is the deeper
tour: UML notation, hierarchical states, and four real-world state
machines you can find running in code you use every day.

## UML state notation

The Unified Modeling Language (UML) formalises a diagramming convention
for state machines. You see it in engineering documents, protocol
specs, and academic papers. Here are the pieces.

**States** are drawn as rounded rectangles or circles. UML also has an
initial state (a solid black dot) and a final state (a black dot with
a ring around it).

```
   (o)-----> INITIAL --> ... --> FINAL -->(*)
```

**Transitions** are labelled arrows between states. The label has the
form:

```
   trigger [ guard ] / action
```

- **trigger:** the event or input that causes the transition.
- **guard:** an optional Boolean condition that must be true.
- **action:** an optional side effect that fires on the transition.

Any of the three parts can be omitted. `tick` alone is a plain
transition on the `tick` event. `[error]/log-and-halt` is a
transition with no trigger, guarded on `error`, doing an action.

**Entry and exit actions** — some states have `entry / do-something`
or `exit / do-something` blocks that run whenever you enter or leave
the state, regardless of which transition brought you.

**Hierarchical states** — a state can contain sub-states. UML lets
you nest state machines inside states, which is very useful for
modeling behaviour with a lot of sub-modes. A CPU's `execute` state,
for example, might contain sub-states for `arithmetic`, `memory-op`,
`branch`, `system-call`.

## Real state machine 1 — TCP

TCP is the transport-layer protocol for most of the internet. Every
TCP connection walks through a state machine defined in RFC 793
(1981) by Jon Postel.

### The states

- **CLOSED** — no connection.
- **LISTEN** — the server is waiting for a client to arrive.
- **SYN-SENT** — the client sent a SYN, waiting for the server's
  SYN-ACK.
- **SYN-RECEIVED** — the server got a SYN, sent its own SYN-ACK,
  waiting for the client's ACK.
- **ESTABLISHED** — the three-way handshake is done. Data can flow.
- **FIN-WAIT-1**, **FIN-WAIT-2**, **CLOSE-WAIT**, **CLOSING**,
  **LAST-ACK**, **TIME-WAIT** — the various closing states.

That is eleven states total. The full state diagram is famously
diamond-shaped and includes shortcuts for various error paths.

### The three-way handshake

Opening a TCP connection is:

```
   client                                    server
     |                                         |
     |----- SYN (seq=X) ----------------------->|
     |                                         |
     |<---- SYN-ACK (seq=Y, ack=X+1) ----------|
     |                                         |
     |----- ACK (ack=Y+1) --------------------->|
     |                                         |
     |=== both now in ESTABLISHED ============|
```

Three packets. Both sides pick a random sequence number, tell the
other, and acknowledge. From then on, every byte gets a sequence
number so out-of-order or lost packets can be detected and resent.

### TCP in Motoi Scheme (sketch)

```
(define (make-tcp-endpoint)
  (let ((state 'CLOSED))
    (lambda (event)
      (set! state
            (case state
              ((CLOSED)
               (case event
                 ((passive-open) 'LISTEN)
                 ((active-open)  'SYN-SENT)
                 (else state)))
              ((LISTEN)
               (case event
                 ((got-syn) 'SYN-RECEIVED)
                 (else state)))
              ((SYN-SENT)
               (case event
                 ((got-syn-ack) 'ESTABLISHED)
                 (else state)))
              ((SYN-RECEIVED)
               (case event
                 ((got-ack) 'ESTABLISHED)
                 (else state)))
              ((ESTABLISHED)
               (case event
                 ((close) 'FIN-WAIT-1)
                 (else state)))
              ;; ... more states omitted for brevity
              (else state)))
      state)))

(define tcp (make-tcp-endpoint))
(tcp 'active-open)     ;; => SYN-SENT
(tcp 'got-syn-ack)     ;; => ESTABLISHED
(tcp 'close)           ;; => FIN-WAIT-1
```

Real TCP has timeouts, retransmissions, congestion control, and the
data-transfer sub-states. But the shape is a state machine, and
Jon Postel drew it in 1981.

## Real state machine 2 — HTTP session

HTTP itself is stateless — each request stands alone — but a browser
session with a server usually maintains state via cookies. That
session is a state machine you can draw.

States:
- **anonymous** — no cookie, no logged-in user.
- **logged-in** — user has authenticated, cookie is valid.
- **admin** — user has elevated privileges.
- **locked-out** — too many failed logins, session revoked.

Transitions include `login-success`, `login-failure` (with a counter
guard), `logout`, `session-timeout`, `admin-elevation`, etc.

Every web app you have ever used has a state machine somewhere in
the auth layer. Sometimes it is drawn explicitly. Sometimes it is
implicit in a hundred `if` statements. The bugs usually live where
somebody forgot to add an `else` branch — an unhandled state
transition.

## Real state machine 3 — Elevator control

An elevator is a physical Mealy machine.

States:
- **idle-at-floor-N** for each floor N.
- **moving-up**, **moving-down**.
- **door-open**, **door-closing**.
- **out-of-service**.

Inputs:
- Button pressed on a floor.
- Button pressed inside the car.
- Door sensor triggered.
- Weight sensor triggered.
- Emergency stop.

Outputs:
- Motor direction, motor speed.
- Door state.
- Floor indicator.

Elevators are famous for having subtle state machines. Building them
correctly is hard because a bug can literally injure people. That is
why elevator control software is heavily verified — often with
formal methods.

## Real state machine 4 — Pac-Man ghost AI

The 1980 Pac-Man arcade game gave each ghost a state machine with
three main states:

- **chase** — pursue Pac-Man according to the ghost's personality.
  (Each ghost had different chase logic: Blinky chases directly,
  Pinky targets four tiles ahead of Pac-Man, etc.)
- **scatter** — retreat to a specific home corner of the maze.
- **frightened** — Pac-Man ate a power pellet; ghosts flee
  randomly and are edible.

The ghost cycles between chase and scatter on timers (typical
alternation: 7 seconds scatter, 20 seconds chase, repeated). When
Pac-Man eats a power pellet, all ghosts jump to frightened for a
few seconds, then return to whatever they were doing.

This tiny state machine is arguably one of the most influential game
AI designs in history. Its simplicity and its emergent complexity —
because the four ghosts have subtly different chase policies — made
Pac-Man feel alive without complex algorithms.

In Motoi Scheme:

```
(define (make-ghost personality)
  (let ((state 'scatter)
        (timer 7))
    (lambda (event)
      (cond
        ((eq? event 'tick)
         (set! timer (- timer 1))
         (when (zero? timer)
           (case state
             ((scatter) (set! state 'chase)   (set! timer 20))
             ((chase)   (set! state 'scatter) (set! timer 7))
             ((frightened) (set! state 'chase) (set! timer 20)))))
        ((eq? event 'power-pellet)
         (set! state 'frightened)
         (set! timer 10)))
      (list 'state state 'timer timer 'personality personality))))

(define blinky (make-ghost 'aggressive-direct-chaser))
(blinky 'tick)              ;; scatter, timer 6
;; ... repeat 6 times ...
(blinky 'power-pellet)      ;; frightened, timer 10
```

That is the shape. Add the maze grid and the movement code and you
have a ghost.

## Nested state machines

Chapter 12's CPU is a state machine with sub-states inside `execute`:
one for each instruction type. That is a hierarchical state machine.
UML lets you draw them as boxes inside boxes.

Another common example is a game character's animation state. The
top-level machine has `idle`, `walking`, `jumping`, `attacking`.
Each of those has sub-states for specific animation frames. A hit
in `attacking` can transition to a `hurt` state which has its own
sub-states for the reaction animation.

Nested state machines let you factor out common transitions.
`emergency-stop` at the top level can be a single transition that
overrides everything below. Without nesting, you would have to
add the transition to every sub-state.

## When to use a state machine

Any time you have a system where:

- The behaviour depends on history, not just current inputs.
- There is a finite set of distinct \"modes\" the system can be in.
- Certain transitions are legal and others are not.

That is a state machine. Draw it before you code it. Name the
states. Enumerate the transitions. **The states and transitions are
the design.**

## When not to use a state machine

If your system has a truly infinite or open-ended state space, a
finite state machine is the wrong tool. Full programming languages
are more expressive. A CPU is a Turing machine, not a finite state
machine (technically), because it has unbounded memory.

But most subsystems inside a program are finite. UI widgets. Auth
flows. Protocol handshakes. Game character AI. Physical device
drivers. All finite. All state machines.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

- State machines are everywhere in real code.
- The formal notation (UML, or just circles and arrows) lets you
  design and communicate without ambiguity.
- Mealy and Moore are equivalent in power; pick whichever presents
  more clearly for your system.
- Hierarchical states let you factor common transitions and keep
  diagrams readable.
- If you draw the state machine before you code, you catch bugs
  the diagram exposes.

## The loop appears

Every state machine has an outer driver loop: read event, transition,
emit, loop. TCP has it. HTTP session has it. Elevator has it. Pac-Man
ghost has it. CPU has it. Chapter 10 named it. Every appendix example
here embodies it.
")
